Certainly! The third conditional is used to discuss hypothetical situations in the past that did not happen. Here's how you can express a hypothetical scenario for John in LaTeX format:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\begin{document}

If John \textbf{had been able to attend university despite his financial constraints}, he \textbf{would have pursued a degree in engineering}. As a result, he \textbf{would have secured a job at a leading tech company} after graduation, which \textbf{would have significantly improved his financial situation}. Consequently, he \textbf{would have been able to support his family comfortably} and \textbf{would have advanced to a senior engineering position} within a few years.

\end{document}
```

This hypothetical scenario outlines how John's life and career might have changed if he had the opportunity to attend university.
